## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: Follow these rules in ALL generated code to prevent runtime crashes.

1) Supabase/query-like results
- Always use nullish coalescing for list data: const items = data ?? [].
- Guard against non-array values: const safeList = Array.isArray(data?.items) ? data.items : [].

2) Array methods
- Never call array methods on potentially null/undefined values without guarding:
  - (items ?? []).map(...)
  - Array.isArray(items) ? items.filter(...) : []

3) React useState for arrays/objects
- Initialize arrays/objects properly:
  - const [sections, setSections] = useState<SectionType[]>([]);
  - Do not use useState() or useState(null) for arrays.

4) API response shapes
- Validate all API responses:
  - const report = Array.isArray(response?.data?.report) ? response.data.report : [];

5) Optional chaining
- Use optional chaining when accessing nested API data:
  - user?.profile?.name, analysis?.report?.sections?.executiveSummary

6) Destructuring with defaults
- Use defaults with destructuring:
  - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {};

7) General
- Never assume data exists; always guard and provide safe fallbacks in UI rendering and data processing.
- All external calls (APIs, storage) should handle failures gracefully with user-friendly messages and retry strategies where appropriate.

